1 bloo d testing at irregular intervals as determined by his or her
2 parole officer.
3 C. The Department of Corrections shall promulgate rules to
4 administer the provisions of this section.
5 D. A physician or mental health professional who acts in good
6 faith in compliance with this section in the administration of
7 treatment shall be immune from and not subject to civil or criminal
8 liability.
9 E. The provisions of this section shall only apply to sex
10 offenders convicted on or after the effective date of this act.
11 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 57 O.S. 2021, Section 332.21, is
12 amended to read as follows:
13 Section 332.21. A. The Pardon and Parole Board is empowered to
14 parole a prisoner who:
15 1. Is sixty (60) years of age or older;
16 2. Has served, in actual custody, the shorter of ten (10) years
17 of the term or terms of imprisonment, or one-third (1/3) of the
18 total term or terms of imprisonment;
19 3. Poses minimal public safety risks warranting continued
20 imprisonment;
21 4. Is not imprisoned for a crime enumerated in Section 13.1 of
22 Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes or Section 571 of Title 57 of the
23 Oklahoma Statutes; and
24
HB2422 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 5. Has not been convicted of a crime that would require the
2 person to be subject to the registration requirements of the Sex
3 Offenders Registration Act.
4 If the prisoner has been convicted for a crime as provided for
5 in paragraphs 4 and 5 of this subsection, the prisoner may be
6 paroled pursuant to the provisions in Section 1 of this act.
7 B. The authority to grant parole under Section 332.2 of Title
8 57 of the Oklahoma Statutes this title shall rest with the Pardon
9 and Parole Board.
10 C. The Pardon and Parole Board shall use an evidence-based
11 risk-assessment instrument to assess the public safety risk posed by
12 aging prisoners upon release.
13 D. Unless eligible for release at an earlier date, an aging
14 prisoner who has been committed to the Department of Corrections for
15 a term or terms of imprisonment shall have the ability to request a
16 parole hearing before the Pardon and Parole Board if the prisoner
17 has served, in actual custody, the shorter of:
18 1. Ten (10) years of the term or terms of actual imprisonment;
19 or
20 2. One-third (1/3) of the total term or terms of imprisonment.
21 E. Once a prisoner requests a parole hearing under subsection A
22 of this section, the Pardon and Parole Board may place the prisoner
23 on the next available docket.
24
